i## That Config is a Function		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iUntil now, we've ignored the first line `{ config, pkgs, ... }:` . In		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifact, the whole `configuration.nix` is a Nix function, and `config`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand `pkgs` are input parameters.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHere's how NixOS defines functions:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # This is a function, with one input "a" and returns (a+1)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  a: a+1		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # This is a function, with one input "a" and returns an object.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # The object has two keys "a" and "b"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # Note that there's no variables in the Nix language!		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # Assuming input is a = 1, the return value will be { a = 2; b = 3; }		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  #                                        instead of { a = 2; b = 4; }		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  a: {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    a = a + 1;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    b = a + 2;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  }		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # This is a function.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # The input is an object with keys "a" and "b".		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # The return value is an object with keys "a" and "b".		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # Assuming input is { a = 1; b = 2; }, the return value will be { a = 2; b = 1; }		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  { a, b }: {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    a = b;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    b = a;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  }		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # This is the same function as the last one,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # just with "..." added to the parameter list,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # so, it accepts (and ignores) unknown parameters.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  #		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # Assuming input is { a = 1; b = 2; c = 3; },		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # the last function will error out since it doesn't recognize "c",		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # but this function will ignore "c" proceed normally		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  { a, b, ... }: {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    a = b;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    b = a;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  }		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBack to the config to install `nyancat` :		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  { config, pkgs, ... }:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
