i## Nix Flake		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSince all NixOS configurations are defined by `configuration.nix` , we		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ican copy the files to another machine, run `nixos-rebuild switch` and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iget an exactly same system. I also stated in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
1the first post of this series	/en/article/modify-website/nixos-why.lantian/	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> (...) one important feature of NixOS is managing each and every		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> package and config with a set of Nix config files. Therefore, we can		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> use any tools we like, for example, Ansible, Rsync, or even Git, to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> manage the config at `/etc/nixos` . Since this is the only config		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> file we care about, we no longer need a bunch of complicated Ansible		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> playbooks or dozens of Rsync commands. We only need to overwrite `/etc/nixos` ,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> run `nixos-rebuild switch` , and call it a day.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
